          <p class="indent-12 mt-8">
            When I wrote <span class="italic">Queers Shoot Back!</span>—my study of radical queer cinema—I leaned heavily on Latin America's Third Cinema of the 1960s, especially Solanas and Getino's militant manifesto that declared film a weapon against imperialism. Indonesia had never crossed my mind. The films I knew from that period—mostly Usmar Ismail's—were psychological dramas of middle-class protagonists confined to bourgeois interiors. They were polite and even “apolitical.” Back then, my own country seemed absent from the militant map.
          </p>

