              Before Solanas and Getino's <span class="italic">The Hour of the Furnaces</span> (1968), there was Bandung—the 1955 Afro-Asian Conference that birthed the idea of the Third World as an anti-imperialist coalition. The conference's spirit soon spilled into culture, culminating in the Afro-Asian Film Festivals in Tashkent (1958), Cairo (1960), and Jakarta (1964). These were the earliest attempts to develop a film culture of the colonised, a cinematic front of the Bandung spirit.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="indent-12 mt-[30px]">
            <span class="italic">Turang</span> was a star of this circuit. Rooted in socialist realism, it depicts Karo villagers in North Sumatra resisting Dutch occupation. But unlike typical war epics centered on soldiers, it foregrounds care, labour, and folk traditions—tending the wounded, cultivating land, singing together—as equally revolutionary acts. Revolution, the film insists, takes a village.
